Abstract
As machine learning (ML) models transition from experimental research to production-grade services, the challenges of scalability, reliability, and deployment velocity become paramount. This project investigates the efficacy of integrating DevOps methodologies and Kubernetes orchestration for the deployment of real-time computer vision models, specifically YOLOv11. Utilizing a remote environment running a Minikube cluster on Arch Linux, we conducted a comparative analysis between traditional manual deployments and an automated, containerized pipeline.
Our experimental results demonstrate that the proposed architecture achieves a 75.8% reduction in deployment latency and a 2.4x increase in peak throughput, reaching over 6,500 requests per second. Furthermore, the implementation of self-healing mechanisms via liveness and readiness probes improved system uptime to 99.7%, significantly reducing the Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR) by 78.6%. This research validates that cloud-native orchestration not only minimizes operational overhead and human error but also provides the elastic scalability necessary for modern AI-driven applications. The findings provide a robust framework for organizations aiming to achieve operational excellence in MLOps.
1. Experimental Setup
1.1 Dataset and Workload Configuration
For the inference workload, the experiment utilizes YOLOv11n, the nano variant of the YOLO (You Only Look Once) architecture. This model was selected for its balance of high-speed inference and low memory footprint, making it ideal for containerized, real-time object detection services.

