1.6 Evaluation Metrics
The system performance was evaluated across four key dimensions to determine the effectiveness of the Kubernetes-based deployment compared to traditional methods.
1. Performance and Scalability Metrics
These metrics measure the responsiveness and resource efficiency of the YOLOv11n inference service.
Latency Profile (ms): End-to-end response time, specifically tracking Mean, P95, and P99 (Tail Latency) to identify performance jitters.
Throughput (RPS): Total successful inference requests processed per second.
Resource Utilization: Percentage of allocated CPU and Memory consumed at the pod and cluster levels.
Pod Count: Number of active replicas under different loads.
HPA Responsiveness: The time delta between a load spike and the Horizontal Pod Autoscaler triggering a replica increase.
2. Reliability and DevOps Metrics
These metrics assess the stability of the orchestration layer and the efficiency of the deployment pipeline.
Error Rate (%): Ratio of failed HTTP requests (5xx/4xx) to total requests.
Self-Healing Capability: Frequency of successful automated pod restarts and Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR) following a simulated failure.
Deployment Velocity: The time required to transition from a code change to a live, stable endpoint in the Minikube cluster.
1.7 Baseline Methods Compared Against
To evaluate the effectiveness of the proposed system, the following three deployment methodologies were compared under identical hardware constraints.
Baseline #1: Monolithic Container Deployment (Docker Compose)
This approach represents a traditional VM-equivalent setup, focusing on functional deployment without operational management.
Workflow: Manual execution via docker-compose.baseline.yml.
Scalability: Restricted to a single container instance; no horizontal scaling.
Resilience: Zero orchestration; manual intervention required for recovery if the container crashes.
Resource Management: Static allocation of CPU and Memory regardless of incoming traffic.
Baseline #2: Manual Containerized Deployment (No Automation)
This represents an intermediate step where the application is containerized but lacks the intelligence of an orchestrator or a CI/CD pipeline.
Workflow: Manual image builds and command-line management.
Scalability: Vertical or manual horizontal scaling (manually spinning up new containers).
Observability: Limited to basic Docker logs and local monitoring.
Deployment: High manual overhead with risk of configuration drift.
Proposed Approach: Automated DevOps + Kubernetes Orchestration
The target architecture leverages a modern Cloud-Native stack to maximize reliability and efficiency.
Orchestration: Full Kubernetes lifecycle management within a Minikube cluster.
Elasticity: Horizontal Pod Autoscaling (HPA) automatically adjusts replica counts based on real-time CPU/Memory metrics.
Self-Healing: Integrated Liveness and Readiness probes ensure traffic is only routed to healthy pods and automatically restart failed instances.
CI/CD & Delivery: Automated image builds with Rolling Update strategies to ensure zero-downtime during model or API updates.
Observability Stack: Deep instrumentation using Prometheus for metrics collection and Grafana for workload visualization.
