2.2 Key Findings: Velocity and Reliability
The transition from manual VM-style management to a full Kubernetes-based CI/CD pipeline yielded the following improvements:
Deployment Velocity: The proposed approach reduced deployment time by ~76% compared to manual methods, enabling faster iteration cycles.
Operational Reliability: Configuration errors were nearly eliminated (reduction from a 40% error rate to <10%) due to the use of standardized Kubernetes manifests and automated build triggers.
Resilience (MTTR): The system's ability to recover from failures improved by 78.6%. The reduction from 42 minutes to 9 minutes highlights the efficiency of Kubernetes' self-healing mechanisms (Liveness/Readiness probes) over manual container restarts.

2.3 Quantitative Results: Scalability and Throughput
The core objective of the scalability test was to measure how the system handles increasing pressure. While manual deployments hit a "performance ceiling" due to fixed resources, the DevOps + Kubernetes approach leveraged Horizontal Pod Autoscaling (HPA) to meet demand dynamically.
