2.4 Scalability Analysis and Key Findings
The data reveals a clear divergence in performance as the workload enters "Heavy Load" territory:
Superior Throughput: At the 5,000-request threshold, the Kubernetes-based approach achieved ~2.95x higher throughput (6,500 req/sec) than the manual baseline. This is directly attributed to the cluster's ability to spin up additional pods to distribute the inference workload.
Performance Plateau: Both the Manual and Containerized-only approaches began to plateau after 1,000 requests. Without an orchestrator to manage resource limits and replication, these systems suffered from resource contention, leading to negligible gains between 1,000 and 5,000 requests.
Latency Stability: Despite a 10x increase in traffic (from 500 to 5,000 requests), the average latency for the proposed approach only increased from 38ms to 85ms. This demonstrates that the system is not only scalable but also maintains a high Quality of Service (QoS) for real-time applications.

