3. Result Analysis
3.1 Deployment Efficiency Analysis
The data illustrates a fundamental shift in operational efficiency when transitioning from Imperative management (Manual) to Declarative orchestration (Kubernetes).

3.1.1 Why the DevOps + Kubernetes Approach Excels:
Elimination of Manual Latency: By utilizing Infrastructure as Code (IaC), the deployment process moves from a series of high-latency human actions (SSH, manual file edits, service restarts) to an automated pipeline. Kubernetes manifests define the "desired state," and the controller works to reach that state instantly, removing the human-in-the-loop bottleneck.
Architectural Integrity and Validation: Manual deployments are prone to "configuration drift." Automation via CI/CD ensures that every deployment is immutable and validated against Kubernetes API schemas before execution. This "gatekeeping" is why the configuration error rate dropped to near zero in the proposed approach.
Autonomous Fault Remediation: The dramatic 78.6% reduction in MTTR (Mean Time to Recovery) is due to Kubernetes' active monitoring. While a manual approach requires a human to detect a failure, diagnose it, and restart the service (averaging 42 minutes), Kubernetes Liveness Probes detect and remediate pod failures in seconds.
Absolute Reproducibility: Version-controlled manifests and container images ensure that the environment is identical across every test run. This eliminates environmental variables as a source of failure, ensuring that the performance metrics captured are consistent and reliable.
3.1.2 Statistical Significance of Results
Confidence Interval: The 76% reduction in deployment time is statistically significant at a 95% confidence level, indicating that these gains are a direct result of the methodology rather than environmental variance.
Error Rate: The shift from a 40% manual error rate to $<10\%$ (attributed primarily to network timeouts rather than logic) demonstrates a tangible improvement in deployment quality.
Operational Impact: The reduction of MTTR from 42 minutes to 9 minutes represents a critical threshold for real-time AI applications, where downtime directly impacts user experience.
3.2 Scalability Analysis
 The experimental data demonstrates a 2.45x average throughput increase when using the proposed Kubernetes architecture. The following factors explain why the system maintains high performance where traditional methods fail.
3.2.1 Why Kubernetes Auto-Scaling Achieves Higher Throughput:
Horizontal Pod Autoscaling (HPA) Dynamics: Traditional deployments are vertically constrained by the resources of a single process. In contrast, the HPA controller monitors real-time CPU utilization (observing a 20-30% baseline). When the load pushes utilization toward the configured threshold (~80%), Kubernetes dynamically provisions additional replicas. This allows the system to scale its compute capacity in direct proportion to the incoming request volume.
Distributed Load Balancing: The Kubernetes Service abstraction acts as a transparent entry point, utilizing a built-in Round-Robin algorithm to distribute traffic across all healthy pods. This ensures that no single pod becomes a bottleneck, optimizing the utilization of the 4-core allocation on the host machine.
Elimination of Performance Plateaus:
Manual/Containerized Baseline: These approaches hit a "performance ceiling" (~2,200–3,150 req/sec) once the primary process reaches resource saturation.
Proposed Approach: By distributing the load, the system avoids this plateau, successfully reaching 6,500 req/sec at the 5,000-user mark.
Predictable Latency and SLA Stability: A key finding is the linear—rather than exponential—latency growth. By scaling out before a pod reaches 100% saturation, the system prevents "performance cliffs," maintaining a low 85ms latency even under heavy stress. This predictability is essential for providing Service Level Agreement (SLA) guarantees in real-world AI applications.
