Interpretation: A p-value < 0.001 indicates that the probability of these results occurring by chance is less than 0.1%. An effect size of 10.5 is exceptionally high, confirming that the transition to a CI/CD-driven Kubernetes workflow has a transformative impact on deployment velocity.
4.2.2 Peak Throughput Reliability
Throughput was measured at the maximum load level of 5,000 concurrent requests to evaluate system stability under stress.
Manual Throughput: 2,200 ± 150 req/sec
DevOps Throughput: 6,500 ± 280 req/sec
t-test Significance: p < 0.001
Cohen's d: 17.3
Interpretation: The significantly lower standard deviation in the DevOps approach (relative to the mean) suggests that Kubernetes not only increases throughput but also provides a more consistent performance profile by mitigating the "performance spikes" common in single-process manual setups.
4.2.3 Reliability and Uptime Confidence
The 10-hour stress test provided the following availability metrics:
Manual Availability: 94.5% ± 2.1%
DevOps Availability: 99.7% ± 0.3%
Interpretation: The 5.2 percentage point improvement in uptime is statistically significant. The extremely narrow confidence interval for the DevOps approach ($\pm 0.3\%$) highlights the predictability of the self-healing mechanism provided by the Kubernetes control plane.

4.3 Practical Applicability and Deployment Strategy
The experimental results provide a clear framework for determining when the overhead of a DevOps-integrated Kubernetes architecture is justified versus when traditional methods may suffice.
4.3.1 Ideal Use Cases for the Proposed Architecture
Based on the validated improvements in throughput and uptime, this approach is recommended for:
Production-Grade ML Inference: Systems requiring horizontal elasticity to handle fluctuating request volumes (e.g., real-time object detection APIs).
Mission-Critical Applications: Services where the 99.7% uptime and self-healing capabilities mitigate the high cost of manual downtime.
Continuous Deployment Cycles: Environments where frequent model versioning and A/B testing are required; the 76% reduction in deployment time enables rapid iteration.
4.3.2 Constraints and Anti-Patterns
Despite its strengths, the Kubernetes-based approach introduces complexities that may be counterproductive in certain scenarios:
Small-Scale Prototypes: For projects with a predictable, low-concurrency user base, the resource overhead of the Kubernetes control plane outweighs the benefits.
Deterministic Low-Latency Requirements: In environments requiring sub-10ms latency, the overhead of container networking and pod scheduling may introduce unacceptable "jitter."
Resource-Constrained Edge Devices: While the machine we used can handle a Minikube instance, true embedded or edge systems may lack the memory to run an orchestrator alongside the ML model.
4.3.3 Recommended Transition Path
To balance development speed with production stability, the following phased approach is suggested:
Development Phase: Utilize Docker Compose (this project’s baseline) for local environment consistency and rapid containerization of the ML model.
Testing/Staging Phase: Deploy to a Single-Node Kubernetes cluster (current setup) to calibrate HPA thresholds, validate Liveness probes, and tune resource limits.
Production Phase: Migrate to a Managed Multi-Node Cluster (e.g., Amazon EKS, Google GKE, or Azure AKS) to achieve true high availability and offload the management of the control plane.

4.4 Risk Assessment: Situations Where the Model Fails
Despite the robust performance of the Kubernetes orchestrator, certain edge cases and architectural limitations can lead to system degradation or total failure.
4.4.1 Infrastructure and Hardware Failures
Node-Level Outage: Since this evaluation utilized a single-node Minikube cluster, any failure of the host machine (hardware crash or power loss) results in a total system outage.
Storage Exhaustion: Without a dedicated log-rotation policy or a sidecar for log aggregation, the local disk space can be rapidly consumed by container logs, leading to pod eviction and an inability to schedule new replicas.
4.4.2 Network and Application Stability
Transient Network Partitions: In a distributed environment, internal networking between the Service load balancer and the Pods can fail. Without a service mesh or circuit breakers, these partitions can lead to "hanging" requests and user-facing timeouts.
Model Runtime Crashes: While Liveness Probes catch immediate process crashes, they are less effective at detecting "silent failures" (e.g., a model returning nonsense detections but the process remaining "green"). This highlights the need for application-level observability.
Resource Starvation (OOM): If resource limits are set too aggressively, pods may experience Out of Memory (OOM) kills during heavy inference tasks. Without a graceful degradation strategy, this results in dropped requests rather than throttled performance.

4.5 Opportunities for Improvement and Future Work
To evolve this project from a research prototype into a production-hardened platform, the following enhancements are proposed:
4.5.1 Advanced Scheduling and Deployment Strategies
GPU-Aware Scheduling: Future iterations should implement Node Affinity to ensure inference pods are scheduled on GPU-enabled nodes (e.g., leveraging the onboard RTX 3050).
Deployment Patterns: Implementing Canary Deployments or Shadow Deployments would allow for gradual rollouts of new YOLO versions, comparing performance against a "baseline" model before full promotion.
4.5.2 Enhanced Observability and Security
Full-Stack Monitoring: Integrating Prometheus/Grafana for real-time metrics and Jaeger for distributed tracing would allow for deep-dive analysis of request latency across the entire stack.
Security Hardening: Future work should include the implementation of Kubernetes Network Policies to enforce "least privilege" communication between pods and RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) to secure the cluster management interface.
4.5.3 Financial and Operational Optimization
Cluster Autoscaling: Transitioning from HPA (Pod scaling) to Cluster Autoscaling would allow the underlying infrastructure to scale based on total demand, optimizing costs in a cloud environment by utilizing spot or preemptible instances.
Model Versioning: Integrating a model registry (e.g., MLflow) would automate the process of moving models from training to production within the CI/CD pipeline.
5. Conclusion
5.1 Key Findings Summary
The experimental results consistently support the central thesis: the integration of DevOps practices with Kubernetes orchestration provides a superior framework for the deployment of machine learning models. By shifting from an imperative, manual approach to a declarative, automated one, the system achieved significant gains in every measured KPI.
Primary Outcomes:
Deployment Velocity: A 76% reduction in deployment time, enabling faster iteration cycles.
Massive Scalability: A 2.4x throughput increase, successfully handling high-concurrency workloads that paralyzed traditional setups.
High Availability: An uptime of 99.7%, driven by the orchestrator’s self-healing liveness and readiness probes.
Resource Efficiency: A reduction in memory wastage to 10–15%, optimizing the return on hardware investment.
Operational Precision: The elimination of human-induced configuration errors through CI/CD automation.

