Appendix: Experimental Configuration Details
A1. Kubernetes Manifest Specifications
The following core manifests defined the desired state of the cluster during the evaluation.
A1.1 Deployment Configuration (k8s/deployment.yaml)
Container Image: yolo-inference-api:v1.1.0 (Debian-slim based).
Resource Management:
requests: CPU: 1.0, Memory: 1Gi.
limits: CPU: 2.0, Memory: 2Gi.
Health Checks:
Liveness Probe: HTTP GET /health (Initial delay: 30s).
Readiness Probe: HTTP GET /ready (Initial delay: 20s).
Environment: Configured for MODEL_PATH=/models/yolov11n.pt and WORKERS=4.
A1.2 Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (k8s/hpa.yaml)
Target Utilization: 70% CPU.
Scaling Limits: Minimum 1 pod; Maximum 5 pods.
Behavior: Scale-up stabilization window of 0 seconds; Scale-down stabilization window of 300 seconds (to prevent "flapping").
A1.3 Service Definition (k8s/service.yaml)
Type: ClusterIP (Internal Load Balancing).
Session Affinity: None (ensuring true round-robin distribution).
Ports: Internal 8000 mapped to Service 8000.

A2. Monitoring and Observability Stack
The observability layer provided the telemetry required for the statistical analysis in Chapter 4.
Prometheus Baseline: Configured with a 15-second scrape interval to capture high-resolution spikes in CPU and memory usage during scaling events.
Grafana Visualization: Four primary dashboards were developed:
Orchestration Health: Real-time pod counts vs. desired state.
Traffic Analytics: Requests per second (RPS) and error rates (4xx/5xx).
Latency Distribution: P50, P95, and P99 response times.
Hardware Metrics: Host CPU/Memory pressure on the IdeaPad Gaming 3.

A3. Load Testing Protocol (Locust)
A distributed load testing approach was used to simulate realistic user traffic patterns.
